   <abstract>I examine whether the FASB's revenue recognition guidance (codified as ASC Topic 606) increases revenue comparability across firms and industries, and whether revenue comparability provides decision useful information to analysts. I extract firms' revenue policy disclosures from 10-K filings to measure the textual similarity of these disclosures in order to compare revenue recognition policies across firms and industries. I find an increase in revenue comparability for economically similar firms in different industries upon adoption of ASC 606, which is consistent with the FASB meeting its objective to improve cross-industry revenue comparability with the new revenue model. In contrast, I find a decrease in revenue comparability for economically similar firms in the same industry. Further, I find evidence consistent with revenue comparability reducing analysts' information processing costs and improving their forecasting performance when covered firms are economically similar, but the benefits of revenue comparability are diminished upon adoption of ASC 606. This finding suggests that the common revenue framework under ASC 606 reduces the usefulness of revenue comparability in the initial years after adoption.</abstract>
